Here’s what that change would do, based on reorder_columns_sot and the TASK 6 drift block in mmm_dev_data_transfer/lambda_function.py.

Names in code
The list uses PaidSocial_impressions and PaidSocial_spend (not PaidSocial_impression / paidsocial_spend). Normalization is case-insensitive for matching, but the canonical names added when a column is missing are the strings in universal_sot_cols.

1. reorder_columns_sot (first universal_sot_cols, ~2157–2178)
That list drives:

Order: SOT columns are placed first, in list order; then retailer-specific spend/impression columns; then everything else.
Missing columns: Any name still in the list but absent from the frame gets created (numeric → 0, Promo_flag → '', Date → '') and an info log.
If you remove OOH_impressions, PaidSocial_impressions, PaidSocial_spend, and TV_impressions:

They are no longer in the “SOT front” block, so they are not auto-added with 0 when missing.
They are not treated as retailer columns either, because media_channels_lower still excludes normalized names like ooh_impressions, paidsocial_impressions, tv_impressions, and the *_spend channel names (~2169–2174).
So if those columns exist in the data, they are picked up only in “Add any remaining columns not in the schema” (~2260–2270): they become trailing “extra” columns (still present, but different position than today—no longer guaranteed right after GQV / with the other universal media fields).
If a file never had one of them, it stays absent (no synthetic column).
OOH_spend and TV_spend stay in the list unless you remove those too; behavior for them is unchanged.

2. Schema drift (second universal_sot_cols, ~3673–3698)
The same list (you should keep both copies in sync) defines what counts as “SOT” for drift:

Removing those four names means the drift loop no longer checks whether those columns are missing from output vs source, so you won’t get TASK 6 classifications or Slack schema-drift signal specifically for those fields from that loop.
extra_cols (~3700–3710) already ignores columns whose normalized names end with _spend, _impressions, or _impression, so those channel columns usually would not have been reported as “extra” even when they were in SOT; removing them from the list mainly changes missing/dropped detection, not “extra” detection for those names.

3. Critical column check (~3739–3741)
critical_cols is only Sales, In_stock_Rate, Promo_flag. Removing the media columns does not by itself trigger that critical error.

Practical summary
Effect	What happens
Column order	OOH/TV/PaidSocial impression (and PaidSocial spend if removed) columns move from fixed SOT prefix to the extras tail (before Promo_flag is forced last).
Missing in file	Those columns are not filled with 0 anymore.
Drift / Slack	Those names are no longer part of the universal SOT drift comparison.
Downstream	Anything assuming walmart.csv-style universal column order or presence of those four may see different layout or absent columns.
If you only edit one of the two universal_sot_cols definitions (~2157 and ~3673), reorder and drift logic will diverge, which is usually a bug—both should match.

